These are the samples forming a separate group-ME019, ME030, ME031 and ME034. Originally identified as A. forsslundi. Re-evaluated by Juha: `All the samples of a taxon that I used to call `A. forsslundi type B` (just A. forsslundi in the data) seem to relate very closely to A. hispida, not A. forsslundi. Therefore, I call them now `A. sp (near hispida)`. They are morfologically easy to separate from normal A. hispida (and forsslundi), but this analysis makes them similar with hispida. So, samples ME040, ME042, ME043, ME044 should be renamed as `A. sp. (near hispida)`.(the reason naming these originally as `A. forsslundi typeB` was because when I borrowed two samples of A. forsslundi from Senkenberg museum / Tobias, there were two forms represented: First was the real forsslundi as in description and the sencond was like this) Juha Salokannel, Mar 6, 2009.

notes: Originally identified as A. forsslundi. Re-evaluated by Juha: `All the samples of a taxon that I used to call `A. forsslundi type B` (just A. forsslundi in the data) seem to relate very closely to A. hispida, not A. forsslundi. Therefore, I call them now `A. sp (near hispida)`. They are morfologically easy to separate from normal A. hispida (and forsslundi), but this analysis makes them similar with hispida. So, samples ME040, ME042, ME043, ME044 should be renamed as `A. sp. (near hispida)`.(the reason naming these originally as `A. forsslundi typeB` was because when I borrowed two samples of A. forsslundi from Senkenberg museum / Tobias, there were two forms represented: First was the real forsslundi as in description and the sencond was like this) Juha Salokannel, Mar 6, 2009.

notes: Originally identified as A. dalecarlicas. Re-evaluated by Juha: `I wasn`t carefull enough when originally determining the samples, and I failed to notice some real A. forsslundi samples among A. dalecarlicas. These are the samples forming a separate group-ME019, ME030, ME031 and ME034. I checked these specimens afterwards, showed them to my colleque and also sent some photos to Wolfgang Tobias-we all agreed that these belong to the correct A. forsslundi.` Juha Salokannel, Mar 6, 2009.

Originally identified as A. forsslundi. Re-evaluated by Juha: `All the samples of a taxon that I used to call `A. forsslundi type B` (just A. forsslundi in the data) seem to relate very closely to A. hispida, not A. forsslundi. Therefore, I call them now `A. sp (near hispida)`. They are morfologically easy to separate from normal A. hispida (and forsslundi), but this analysis makes them similar with hispida. So, samples ME040, ME042, ME043, ME044 should be renamed as `A. sp. (near hispida)`.(the reason naming these originally as `A. forsslundi typeB` was because when I borrowed two samples of A. forsslundi from Senkenberg museum / Tobias, there were two forms represented: First was the real forsslundi as in description and the sencond was like this) Juha Salokannel, Mar 6, 2009.

ID confirmed by Juha: `There may be some kind of problem with ME070, which is the only sample I`ve determined as A. zonella, but went somewhere else than other zonellas (it is among dalecarlicas). I rechecked the determination and I still think it is zonella. I don`t know what to do with that.` Juha Salokannel, Mar 6, 2009.

notes:
Originally identified as A. dalecarlica by S. Chuluunbat.

Re-evaluated by John Morse: `This specimen has the abdomen cleared and preserved in a microvial of glycerin on the pin. I have examined the genitalia and compared them with the illustrations provided by Levanidova & Arefina (1997, in P.A. Lera) and by Malicky (2004). This female specimen varies somewhat from those illustrated, but certainly is much closer to the illustrations of Apatania zonella than to that of A. hispida or any other species illustrated by those authors.` Apr 2, 2009.

S. Chuluunbat noted: `If the specimen looks different than A. hispida, then it is A. dalecarlica. This species is not illustrated in the Levanidova and Arefina. I have looked the A. zonella from Fin and it resembles to the Levanidova and Arefina`s illustrations. I have also looked A. dalecarlica from Fin and our specimens resembles to A. dalecarlica.` Apr 5, 2009.
